160a2b02 [scudmarks@discord] the sound is very similar to splash screen of williams arcade machines, any ideas of the algorithms / effects at play in their 6800 code?
160a2f6a [kimi-k2.5] #The sonic signature you're hearing—the crackling, swept "white noise whoosh"—comes from
160a2f6a [kimi-k2.5] #software-synthesized stochastic audio on the Williams 6800 hardware. Both the laser cleaner
160a2f6a [kimi-k2.5] #and the Williams splash screens produce band-limited noise with amplitude modulation and
160a2f6a [kimi-k2.5] #frequency sweep characteristics, though via entirely different physical mechanisms.
160a2f6a [kimi-k2.5] #
160a2f6a [kimi-k2.5] #Williams 6800 Sound Architecture
160a2f6a [kimi-k2.5] #
160a2f6a [kimi-k2.5] #Williams machines (Defender, Robotron, Joust, Stargate) used a dedicated Motorola 6800 CPU
160a2f6a [kimi-k2.5] #driving an 8-bit DAC directly—no AY-3-8910, no SID, no POKEY. The 6800 spent ~90% of its cycles
160a2f6a [kimi-k2.5] #in tight interrupt service routines (ISRs) calculating waveform samples and blasting them to the
160a2f6a [kimi-k2.5] #DAC at ~8-10kHz.
160a2f6a [kimi-k2.5] #
160a2f6a [kimi-k2.5] #The "splash screen" algorithm (often called the "swoosh" or "wipe" effect) typically combined three
160a2f6a [kimi-k2.5] #elements:
160a2f6a [kimi-k2.5] #
160a2f6a [kimi-k2.5] #1. LFSR White Noise Generator
160a2f6a [kimi-k2.5] #The stochastic crackle came from a Linear Feedback Shift Register (LFSR)—usually 16-bit or
160a2f6a [kimi-k2.5] #24-bit with taps at bits 16, 15, 1, 0 (XORed together). This produced pseudo-random values that
160a2f6a [kimi-k2.5] #sound like acoustic white noise when streamed to the DAC.
160a2f6a [kimi-k2.5] #
160a2f6a [kimi-k2.5] #
160a2f6a [kimi-k2.5] #; 6800 pseudocode - LFSR noise generator
160a2f6a [kimi-k2.5] #NOISE:  LSR NOISE_HI    ; Shift right
160a2f6a [kimi-k2.5] #        ROR NOISE_LO    ; Rotate through carry
160a2f6a [kimi-k2.5] #        BCC NO_OUT      ; If carry clear, output
160a2f6a [kimi-k2.5] #        LDA NOISE_LO    ; Get random value
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #        EOR #$FF        ; Invert (optional for balance)
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #        STAA DAC        ; Output to DAC
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #NO_OUT: RTS
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #2. Frequency Sweep via Decimation
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #To create the "sweeping" quality (like the laser moving across the screen), the code decimated
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #the LFSR output—updating the DAC only every N cycles, where N increased
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #exponentially or linearly over time. This effectively lowers the cutoff frequency of the noise,
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #creating the characteristic downward pitch sweep from "hiss" to "thump."
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #// Conceptual C for the sweep logic
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #uint16_t lfsr = 0xACE1;
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #uint8_t decimation = 1;      // Start fast (high frequency)
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #uint8_t decay = 255;         // Amplitude envelope
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #while(decay > 0) {
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #    if(--decimation == 0) {
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #        // Tap LFSR
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #        lfsr = (lfsr >> 1) ^ (-(lfsr & 1u) & 0xB400);
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #        // Output with amplitude envelope
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #        DAC = ((lfsr & 0xFF) * decay) >> 8;
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #        decimation = sweep_rate++;  // Slow down update = lower pitch
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #        decay -= envelope_step;     // Fade out
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #    }
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #}
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #3. Amplitude Envelope
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #An exponential decay table (stored in ROM) multiplied the raw noise values, creating the "doppler
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #fade" as the "splash" completes.
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #Why They Sound Identical
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #╭───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┬────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #│  Laser Cleaner                                                                    │  Williams 6800 Code                                        │
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #├───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #│  **Plasma micro-explosions** create random acoustic impulses                      │  **LFSR bit transitions** create random digital impulses   │
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #│  **Sweep velocity** modulates the rate of popping (Doppler-like)                  │  **Decimation rate** modulates the noise cutoff frequency  │
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #│  **Surface irregularities** cause amplitude variation (some spots ablate louder)  │  **Envelope generator** causes amplitude decay             │
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #│  **Broadband "crackle"** from stochastic vaporization                             │  **Broadband "crackle"** from pseudo-random bitstream      │
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #╰───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┴────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #Both are impulse-driven broadband noise sources with swept low-pass filtering—the laser
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #acoustically filters itself as it moves (directionality and distance effects), while the 6800
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #mathematically filtered the LFSR by skipping samples.
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #Specific Williams Implementation
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #Eugene Jarvis and Larry DeMar often used a "swept noise table" rather than real-time LFSR
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #for the splash effect in later games (Robotron onward). They pre-calculated 256-512 samples of
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #white noise with an integrated envelope, then played it back with a variable phase
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #increment—essentially wavetable synthesis where the playback rate slowed down over time,
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #stretching the noise and lowering its apparent pitch simultaneously.
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #This creates that distinctive "electric waterfall" sound that fades into sub-bass
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #rumble—mathematically identical to the sound of a laser cleaner sweeping across a rusted surface
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #where the pop density decreases as the beam moves away or the debris clears.
160a2f6b [kimi-k2.5] #
