160a559b [scudmarks@discord] how about mods that enhance original roms, is that a thing?
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #Yes, ROM hacking/enhancement patches for Williams 6800 coin-ops exist, though the scene is
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #smaller than console hacking (NES/SNES) due to the hardware barrier—you need the actual PCB or
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #accurate emulation to test.
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #The Technical Reality
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #6800 ROM mods are feasible because:
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #- Flat memory maps: Early Williams games (Defender, Stargate) use straightforward 16KB–48KB
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #ROM layouts without encryption
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #- Assembly-level patches: Hacks modify specific subroutines—e.g., changing `$A1B4` from
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #`DEC LIVES` to `NOP NOP` for infinite lives, or tweaking the LFSR seed values we discussed to alter
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #sound timbres
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #- Checksum bypass: Many boards have ROM checksum verification; mods must patch the checksum
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #routine or recalculate the expected values
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #Common Enhancement Types
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #• Bug fixes*: Defender has a notorious ship-spawn bug where you can crash immediately on
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #new life. Community patches fix the initialization timing.
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #• Difficulty balancing*: "Turbo" variants increase enemy counts or speed beyond the
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #255-maximum limitations of the original counters (requires changing `CMP #$FF` to higher values
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #with bank switching).
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #• Sound modifications*: Hacks that replace the LFSR polynomials or envelope
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #rates—essentially the sonic "mods" you were theorizing about.
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #• Multi-region*: Converting "Red Label" Defender to "Green Label" behavior (official ROM
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #revisions treated as "mods" by the community).
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #The Legal Trap You Identified
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #Since these ROMs remain commercially active (Midway Arcade Origins, etc.), distributing
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #complete modified ROM images is straightforward copyright infringement—no different than
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #distributing a patched Mario ROM.
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #The patch model (IPS/UPS/BPS files) exists in a deliberate gray area:
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #- The patch contains only the differences (XOR deltas)
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #- User must supply the original copyrighted ROM
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #- Legal theory: No copyrighted bytes distributed; only instructions to transform
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #- Reality: Still likely contributory infringement, but unenforced for abandoned titles (which these
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #are not, as you noted)
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #The Williams-Specific Wrinkle
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #Williams' later 6800 games (Sinistar, Bubbles) used ROM banking and watchdog timers
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #that make naive mods crash the hardware. The enhancement scene requires understanding the specific
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #memory-mapped I/O (C000–CFFF range) and the dual-6800 synchronization in Robotron/Stargate.
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #• Bottom line*: Technically trivial for a 6800 assembly programmer; legally problematic
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #given current commercial availability; ethically contested between "archival preservation" and
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #"active IP violation."
160a5785 [kimi-k2.5] #
