160a6858 [scudmarks@discord] what is state of atari vector game machines, is it possible to build a vector display with modern components without resorting to raster based emulation?
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #Original Atari vector hardware (Asteroids, Tempest, Star Wars, Battlezone) survives in collector
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #hands but faces a catastrophic parts shortage: the specialized Wells-Gardner and Amplifone
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #XY monitors are irreplaceable, and the custom vector generator ASICs (POKEY variants, AVG/IVG
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #chips) are increasingly scarce.
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #True Vector Without Raster Emulation
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #• Yes, absolutely possible*, but requires abandoning the CRT-specific deflection approach
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #in favor of modern vector projection or display technologies:
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #1. Laser Galvanometer Systems
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #The most viable modern vector display. Two-axis galvanometer mirrors steer a laser beam with
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #microsecond precision—essentially the same principle as Atari's electron beam steering, but with
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #photons instead of electrons.
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #- Commercial: Pangolin FB3/FB4 controllers accept vector data via ILDA protocol
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #- DIY: Teensy 4.1 + DAC (MCP4922) driving Chinese galvos (~$200) can render Asteroids at
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #30k points/second
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #- Trade-off: No phosphor persistence, so "trail" effects require deliberate frame buffering
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #(unlike CRT afterglow)
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #2. Oscilloscope Vector Conversion
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #X-Y mode on modern digital scopes (Rigol, Siglent) accepts analog voltages to drive the display
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #directly. Vector game PCBs output X/Y/Z (brightness) analog signals naturally—just need level
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #shifting to ±5V or ±10V scope inputs.
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #- Limitation: Small screen, non-square aspect ratio, burn-in risk with persistence modes
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #- Advantage: True analog deflection, no pixels, perfect mathematical purity
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #3. Vector Monitors from Test Equipment
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #Surplus storage tube displays (Tektronix 4010 series) or analog radar scopes provide genuine
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #large-format vector display, though refresh rates are poor compared to gaming requirements.
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #4. Custom Electromagnetic Deflection
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #Building a CRT-based XY monitor from scratch is theoretically possible but practically insane: you
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #need custom-wound yokes, high-voltage flyback transformers, and 50MHz+ deflection amplifiers. A few
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #hobbyists have done it; none have mass-produced it.
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #The Modern Bottleneck
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #Atari's vector hardware generated analog X/Y/Z signals at 1-4 MHz update rates. Modern
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #solutions must replicate that analog bandwidth:
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #Original Atari AVG (Analog Vector Generator)
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #    ↓
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #Digital Vector Data (6502/vector state machine)
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #    ↓
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #DAC (10-bit, ~2MHz update)
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #    ↓
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #Deflection Amplifier (±70V, 10MHz bandwidth)
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #    ↓
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #CRT Yoke (magnetic deflection)
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #• Modern equivalent:*
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #Teensy 4.1 or FPGA
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #    ↓
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #Dual DAC (MCP4822, SPI, 12-bit)
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #    ↓
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #Galvo driver amplifier (±10V, analog servo loop)
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #    ↓
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #Galvanometer mirrors (600°/s slew rate)
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #The "MAME Problem"
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #Standard MAME vector emulation rasterizes lines into pixel buffers. This destroys:
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #- Line thickness modulation (varying Z-axis intensity changes line width on real vectors;
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #raster just changes alpha)
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #- Phosphor bloom (the CRT glow physics)
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #- Infinite resolution (lines have no pixel edges in true vector)
160a6a19 [kimi-k2.5] #
