161a3792 [kimi-k2.5] #The symbol ℘ (U+2118) denotes the Weierstrass elliptic function, introduced by Karl
161a3792 [kimi-k2.5] #Weierstrass in his mid-19th-century work on complex analysis (specifically in his 1856 memoirs on
161a3792 [kimi-k2.5] #Abelian functions and later lectures in Berlin).
161a3792 [kimi-k2.5] #
161a3792 [kimi-k2.5] #• Key points:*
161a3792 [kimi-k2.5] #
161a3792 [kimi-k2.5] #• Etymology: It is a stylized calligraphic lowercase "p," chosen by Weierstrass to
161a3792 [kimi-k2.5] #represent his specific elliptic function \wp(z; g2, g3), defined by the series:
161a3792 [kimi-k2.5] #    \wp(z) = 1⁄z² + \sum_ω \neq 0 \left( 1⁄(z-ω)² - 1⁄ω² \right)
161a3792 [kimi-k2.5] #    over lattice periods ω.
161a3792 [kimi-k2.5] #
161a3792 [kimi-k2.5] #• Usage: It became standard notation in elliptic function theory (along with invariants
161a3792 [kimi-k2.5] #g2, g3 and derivative \wp') to distinguish it from Jacobian elliptic functions (sn, cn,
161a3792 [kimi-k2.5] #dn).
161a3792 [kimi-k2.5] #
161a3792 [kimi-k2.5] #• Unicode: Added to Unicode 1.0 (1991) as "SCRIPT CAPITAL P" despite functioning as a
161a3792 [kimi-k2.5] #lowercase mathematical symbol—a historical naming quirk carried over from early character sets.
161a3792 [kimi-k2.5] #
161a3792 [kimi-k2.5] #It remains the standard symbol in algebraic geometry and number theory for the Weierstrass
161a3792 [kimi-k2.5] #\wp-function associated with elliptic curves.
161a3792 [kimi-k2.5] #
