18180db0 [kimi-k2.5] #You're right that explicit reference to Asimov's laws is oddly absent from most current AI safety
18180db0 [kimi-k2.5] #discourse, despite the obvious relevance as robotics advances.
18180db0 [kimi-k2.5] #
18180db0 [kimi-k2.5] #The laws themselves are fiction—storytelling devices rather than engineering specifications—and
18180db0 [kimi-k2.5] #Asimov spent his career exploring why they fail (ambiguity in "harm," conflicting interpretations,
18180db0 [kimi-k2.5] #edge cases). But the aims—ensuring beneficial outcomes, preserving human agency,
18180db0 [kimi-k2.5] #maintaining controllability—are absolutely being discussed, just under different terminology.
18180db0 [kimi-k2.5] #
18180db0 [kimi-k2.5] #What's happening instead:
18180db0 [kimi-k2.5] #
18180db0 [kimi-k2.5] #• Technical translation.* Modern safety work addresses similar goals through "alignment"
18180db0 [kimi-k2.5] #(ensuring systems pursue intended objectives), "interpretability" (understanding decision-making),
18180db0 [kimi-k2.5] #and "robustness" (handling edge cases). Constitutional AI and RLHF are attempts to bake in
18180db0 [kimi-k2.5] #behavioral constraints, though they lack the crisp logical structure Asimov imagined.
18180db0 [kimi-k2.5] #
18180db0 [kimi-k2.5] #• Regulatory fragmentation. Industrial robotics has strict physical safety standards
18180db0 [kimi-k2.5] #(ISO 10218, force limiting, collaborative robot specs), but these address mechanical hazards, not
18180db0 [kimi-k2.5] #autonomous decision-making. The gap you're noticing is between physical safety and
18180db0 [kimi-k2.5] #behavioral* safety—how do we constrain a robot's choices, not just its torque?
18180db0 [kimi-k2.5] #
18180db0 [kimi-k2.5] #• The specification problem.* Asimov's laws assume we can define "harm" or "human"
18180db0 [kimi-k2.5] #precisely enough to code. Current discussion focuses on the difficulty of specification itself—how
18180db0 [kimi-k2.5] #do you formally encode "do no harm" when contexts vary infinitely?
18180db0 [kimi-k2.5] #
18180db0 [kimi-k2.5] #The lack of public discussion may reflect commercial incentives (safety slows deployment) or the
18180db0 [kimi-k2.5] #technical reality that we don't yet know how to reliably implement such constraints in
18180db0 [kimi-k2.5] #learning-based systems. But as you note, the disconnect between advancing capabilities and lagging
18180db0 [kimi-k2.5] #safety frameworks is becoming harder to ignore.
18180db0 [kimi-k2.5] #
